Sentencas: This paper established a numerical model for a solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC) button cell, focusing on the effects of finger-like channels on the gas transport process in the anode support.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: The current densities of channelled button cell and un-channelled button cell are compared at different operating temperature and voltage with H-2 as the fuel.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: The H-2 transport is discussed in detail, such as the mole fraction distribution of H-2 in the porous layer, the diffusion flux and convective flux of H-2.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: It is found that the performance of SOFC can be improved by 2.60 % at 800 A degrees C, 0.5 V, compared with un-channelled SOFC due to the improved gas transport by the finger-like channels.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: Then, the model is further extended to study 2D-planar SOFC fuelled with syngas.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: The mole fraction gradients of H-2, CO, CH4 and CO are all substantially reduced by the finger-like channels compared to un-channelled planar cell.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: It is found that the SOFC performance is improved by 5.93 % at 800 A degrees C, 0.5 V, when syngas fuel is used.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: The present study clearly demonstrated that the use of finger-like channels in the anode support is effective in improving the gas transport and the SOFC performance.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application

Sentencas: The present model can be employed for subsequent optimization of the channel configuration for further performance improvement.
Titulo: Modelling of finger-like channelled anode support for SOFCs application
